- ## Requirement

A requirement refines a goal by sa- tisfying three properties: (i) it is described entirely in terms of values monitored by the software; (ii) it con- strains only values that are controlled by the software; and (iii) the controlled values are not defined in terms of future monitored values.

ReqMon’s MAL is important. As an intermediate language, MAL simplifies monitor optimization analysis and ensures traceability between requirements and their observable events. ReqMon’s MAL is sandwiched be- tween the high-level requirements and the low-level events. The MAL defines monitoring templates within an object-oriented, real-time temporal logic language [40, 87]. ReqMon Designer assists in deriving and im- plementing MAL monitors.

- ## Monitors
#Monitors #ReqMon #Frameworks #Requirements #Monitoring 
Monitors execute like a real-time rule-based black- board system: 1. A source raises an event. 2. A sink acquires the event, thereby becoming a fact in the monitoring system. 3. Each monitor of a sink determines if the new event matches. If so, it determines the value of its mon- itored requirements, and raises new events as neces- sary. Monitors can generate events as part of their execu- tion. Thus, monitors can monitor both directly ob- servable events and monitor results.

ReqMon uses the KAOS language, patterns, and some methodology for its requirements, and monitor defini- tions [16]. The language makes use of real-time temporal operators [50], including: some time in the future ð}Þ; the next state (o), the previous state (•), some time in the past (t), always in the past (m), always in the future (o), always in the future unless (W), and always in the future until (U). The language also makes use of the standard logical connectives:  (and),  (or), ‹ (not), fi (implies), M (equivalent), g (entails)
